---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "The Complete IUD Guide: Hormonal vs. Copper, Insertion, and Side Effects",
    "description": "Everything you need to know about Intrauterine Devices (IUDs), including the differences between hormonal and copper options, the insertion process, and common side effects.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "The Nookie Nook"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does IUD insertion hurt?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Many people experience cramping or a sharp pinch during insertion. Pain levels vary significantly from person to person. Taking ibuprofen beforehand or discussing local anesthesia with your provider can help."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can an IUD get lost inside me?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. An IUD is placed in the uterus, and the cervix prevents it from moving to other parts of your body. Occasionally, the strings can curl up, making them hard to feel, but the device remains in the uterus."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I use a menstrual cup with an IUD?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, but it requires caution. Be sure to break the suction seal of the menstrual cup before removing it to avoid accidentally pulling on the IUD strings and dislodging the device."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];
---

<SiteLayout
  site="nookienook"
  title="The Complete IUD Guide: Hormonal vs Copper"
  description="Everything you need to know about Intrauterine Devices (IUDs), including the differences between hormonal and copper options, insertion, and side effects."
  canonical="https://thenookienook.com/iud-guide-complete"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>The Complete IUD Guide</h1>
      <p>Navigating hormonal vs. copper options, the insertion process, and what to expect.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <p>Intrauterine Devices (IUDs) are small, T-shaped devices inserted into the uterus to prevent pregnancy. They are highly effective, long-lasting, and reversible, making them a popular choice for many. This guide covers the different types of IUDs, what insertion feels like, and the facts behind common myths.</p>

      <h2>Hormonal vs. Copper IUDs</h2>
      <p>There are two main categories of IUDs: hormonal and non-hormonal (copper). Both are over 99% effective, but they work differently.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Hormonal IUDs (Mirena, Liletta, Kyleena, Skyla)</h3>
        <p>Hormonal IUDs release a steady, small amount of progestin locally into the uterus. This thickens cervical mucus (blocking sperm) and thins the uterine lining.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Duration:</strong> Depending on the brand, they last between 3 to 8 years.</li>
          <li><strong>Periods:</strong> Often lead to lighter, shorter periods, and many users stop having periods entirely after a year.</li>
          <li><strong>Side Effects:</strong> Irregular bleeding initially, breast tenderness, or mild hormonal side effects.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>The Copper IUD (Paragard)</h3>
        <p>The copper IUD is completely hormone-free. The copper wire wrapped around the device creates a toxic environment for sperm, acting as a highly effective spermicide.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Duration:</strong> Approved for up to 10 years, though research indicates it may be effective for up to 12.</li>
          <li><strong>Periods:</strong> Often causes heavier, longer, and more painful periods, especially in the first 3-6 months.</li>
          <li><strong>Side Effects:</strong> Increased cramping, spotting between periods.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>The Insertion Process</h2>
      <p>The thought of IUD insertion can be intimidating, but knowing what to expect can help ease anxiety.</p>

      <p>The procedure is typically quick, taking only about 5-10 minutes. Here is the general process:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Your provider will examine your pelvis to find the exact position of your uterus.</li>
        <li>A speculum is inserted to visualize the cervix.</li>
        <li>The provider will clean your cervix and vagina with an antiseptic solution.</li>
        <li>A specialized instrument may be used to gently align the cervix and uterus.</li>
        <li>The IUD is folded into a thin tube, passed through the cervix, and pushed into the uterus where it opens into its T-shape.</li>
      </ol>

      <p><strong>Managing Pain:</strong> Pain levels vary widely. Some experience a strong, sharp cramp, while others feel only mild discomfort. Speak with your healthcare provider about pain management options beforehand, which may include ibuprofen, a cervical block (local anesthesia), or medication to soften the cervix.</p>

      <h2>Side Effects and Aftercare</h2>
      <p>Following insertion, it's normal to experience cramping and spotting for a few days to a few weeks. Heating pads and over-the-counter pain relievers can help. Your provider will leave two thin threads (strings) hanging slightly out of the cervix, allowing you to check that the IUD is still in place.</p>
      <p>If you experience severe pain, heavy bleeding that soaks through a pad in an hour, foul-smelling discharge, or unexplained fever, contact your doctor immediately.</p>

      <h2>Common Myths Debunked</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Myth: IUDs cause infertility.</strong> Fact: Fertility returns almost immediately after removal.</li>
        <li><strong>Myth: You can't get an IUD if you haven't had a baby.</strong> Fact: IUDs are safe and commonly prescribed for people who have never given birth.</li>
        <li><strong>Myth: My partner will feel it during sex.</strong> Fact: While some partners may occasionally feel the strings, it shouldn't cause pain. If it does, the strings can often be trimmed by your doctor.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Further Reading</h2>
